            <span class="sect2"><a href=
            "ch06s03.html#id4785823">Attributes</a></span>
          </dt>
        </dl>
      </div>
      <div class="sect2" lang="en" xml:lang="en">
        <div class="titlepage">
          <h3 class="title">
            <a name="id4784523" id="id4784523"></a>Introduction
          </h3>
        </div>
        <p>
          There is two categories of button: <span class=
          "emphasis"><em>sort</em></span> and <span class=
          "emphasis"><em>swap</em></span>.
        </p>
        <p>
          The <span class="emphasis"><em>swap</em></span> buttons are included
          since origin, while the <span class="emphasis"><em>sort</em></span>
          buttons were included in the 0.5.0 version.
        </p>
        <p>
          With <span class="bold"><strong>swap</strong></span> buttons, you
          will do your selection easily. Select item(s) (one or more), from
          unselected or selected list, then clic on the <span class=
          "emphasis"><em>add</em></span> or <span class=
          "emphasis"><em>remove</em></span> button to move your selection from
          one list to the other.
        </p>
        <div class="tip c2">
          <table border="0" summary="Tip">
            <tr>
              <td rowspan="2" align="center" valign="top" width="48">
                <img alt="[Tip]" src="img/admons/tip.png" />
              </td>
              <th align="left">
                Tip
              </th>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td align="left" valign="top">
                You can also double-clic on one item to move it, immediately,
                to the other list without to clic on the <span class=
                "emphasis"><em>add</em></span> or <span class=
                "emphasis"><em>remove</em></span> button.
              </td>
            </tr>
          </table>
        </div>
        <p>
          Since version 1.1.0 you have ability to select or unselect all items
          in one stroke. You may also toggle a previous selection. This new
          feature is available through buttons <span class=
          "emphasis"><em>all</em></span>, <span class=
          "emphasis"><em>none</em></span> and <span class=
          "emphasis"><em>toggle</em></span>.
        </p>
        <p>
          Since version 1.2.0 toggle selection feature is available for both
          single and dual multi-select boxes.
        </p>
        <div class="note c2">
          <table border="0" summary="Note">
            <tr>
              <td rowspan="2" align="center" valign="top" width="48">
                <img alt="[Note]" src="img/admons/note.png" />
              </td>
              <th align="left">
                Note
              </th>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td align="left" valign="top">
                <div class="itemizedlist">
                  <ul type="disc">
                    <li>with one multi-select list, buttons available are only:
                    <span class="emphasis"><em>all</em></span>, <span class=
                    "emphasis"><em>none</em></span> and <span class="emphasis">
                      <em>toggle</em></span>.
                    </li>
                    <li>with two multi-select list, buttons available are only:
                    <span class="emphasis"><em>add</em></span>, <span class=
                    "emphasis"><em>remove</em></span>, <span class="emphasis">
                      <em>moveup</em></span>, <span class=
                      "emphasis"><em>movedown</em></span>, <span class=
                      "emphasis"><em>all</em></span>, <span class=
                      "emphasis"><em>none</em></span> and <span class=
                      "emphasis"><em>toggle</em></span>.
                    </li>
                  </ul>
                </div>
              </td>
            </tr>
          </table>
        </div>
        <p>
          A full example is given in appendices. See the <a href=
          "ch09s03.html#examples.custom.7" title="">advanced selection</a>.
        </p>
        <p>
          With <span class="bold"><strong>sort</strong></span> buttons, you
          have ability to reorder your selection easily. Select one item then
          clic on the <span class="emphasis"><em>up</em></span> or <span class=
          "emphasis"><em>down</em></span> button to move it to the top or the
          bottom of your selection.
        </p>
        <div class="note c2">
          <table border="0" summary="Note">
            <tr>
              <td rowspan="2" align="center" valign="top" width="48">
                <img alt="[Note]" src="img/admons/note.png" />
              </td>
              <th align="left">
                Note
              </th>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td align="left" valign="top">
                Order is keep in the $_POST super global array, when the form
                is submit; Even if you've activated the auto-arrange feature
                (see <em class="parameter"><code>$sort</code></em> parameter of
                the <a href="re01.html" title=
                "constructor HTML_QuickForm_advmultiselect::HTML_QuickForm_advmultiselect">
                HTML_QuickForm_advmultiselect class constructor</a> )
              </td>
            </tr>
          </table>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="sect2" lang="en" xml:lang="en">
        <div class="titlepage">
          <h3 class="title">
            <a name="id4785751" id="id4785751"></a>Appearance
          </h3>
        </div>
        <p>
          There is two kinds of button: <span class=
          "emphasis"><em>text</em></span> and <span class=
          "emphasis"><em>image</em></span>. These are the standard html buttons
          we can find in a form. Default appearance is <span class=
          "emphasis"><em>text</em></span> but you can also easily use
          <span class="emphasis"><em>image</em></span> layout. Here is how to
          do :
        </p>
        <div class="php c3">
          <ol>
            <li class="li1">
              <div class="de1">
                <span class="kw2">&lt;?php</span>
              </div>
            </li>
            <li class="li1">
              <div class="de1">
                <span class="re0">$ams</span>-&gt;<span class=
                "me1">setButtonAttributes</span><span class=
                "br0">(</span><span class="st0">'add'</span>,&nbsp; &nbsp;
                <span class="kw3">array</span><span class=
                "br0">(</span><span class="st0">'type'</span> =&gt;
                <span class="st0">'image'</span>, <span class=
                "st0">'src'</span> =&gt; <span class=
                "st0">'/img/add.png'</span><span class=
                "br0">)</span><span class="br0">)</span>;
              </div>
            </li>
            <li class="li1">
              <div class="de1">
                <span class="re0">$ams</span>-&gt;<span class=
                "me1">setButtonAttributes</span><span class=
                "br0">(</span><span class="st0">'remove'</span>, <span class=
                "kw3">array</span><span class="br0">(</span><span class=
                "st0">'type'</span> =&gt; <span class="st0">'image'</span>,
                <span class="st0">'src'</span> =&gt; <span class=
                "st0">'/img/remove.png'</span><span class=
                "br0">)</span><span class="br0">)</span>;
              </div>
            </li>
            <li class="li1">
              <div class="de1">
                <span class="kw2">?&gt;</span>
              </div>
            </li>
          </ol>
        </div>
        <p>
          Of course, all images are supported: PNG, GIF, etc ...
        </p>
        <div class="caution c2">
          <table border="0" summary="Caution">
            <tr>
              <td rowspan="2" align="center" valign="top" width="48">
                <img alt="[Caution]" src="img/admons/caution.png" />
              </td>
              <th align="left">
                Caution
              </th>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td align="left" valign="top">
                If the image file does not exist, you will get the internal
                text value as output without nothing else.
                <p>
                  Remember that defaults are: "<span class="quote"><code class=
                  "literal">&gt;&gt;</code></span> " for add button, and
                  "<span class="quote"><code class=
                  "literal">&lt;&lt;</code></span> " for remove button.
                </p>
              </td>
            </tr>
          </table>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="sect2" lang="en" xml:lang="en">
        <div class="titlepage">
          <h3 class="title">
            <a name="id4785823" id="id4785823"></a>Attributes
          </h3>
        </div>
        <p>
          In version 0.4.0, there were only the basic <span class=
          "emphasis"><em>add</em></span> and <span class=
          "emphasis"><em>remove</em></span> buttons. In version 0.5.0, two new
          buttons were added: <span class="emphasis"><em>moveup</em></span> and
          <span class="emphasis"><em>movedown</em></span>. In version 1.1.0,
          three new buttons were added: <span class=
          "emphasis"><em>all</em></span>, <span class=
          "emphasis"><em>none</em></span>, and <span class=
          "emphasis"><em>toggle</em></span>.
        </p>
        <div class="caution c2">
          <table border="0" summary="Caution">
            <tr>
              <td rowspan="2" align="center" valign="top" width="48">
                <img alt="[Caution]" src="img/admons/caution.png" />
              </td>
              <th align="left">
                Caution
              </th>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td align="left" valign="top">
                Any other button identifier than <span class=
                "bold"><strong>add</strong></span>, <span class=
                "bold"><strong>remove</strong></span>, <span class=
                "bold"><strong>all</strong></span>, <span class=
                "bold"><strong>none</strong></span>, <span class=
                "bold"><strong>toggle</strong></span>, <span class=
                "bold"><strong>moveup</strong></span>, <span class=
                "bold"><strong>movedown</strong></span> will throws a
                PEAR_Error.
              </td>
            </tr>
          </table>
        </div>
        <p>
          Only five attributes may be set, with these four button identifiers;
          they are:
        </p>
        <div class="variablelist">
          <dl>
            <dt>
              <span class="term"><em class=
              "parameter"><code>name</code></em></span>
            </dt>
            <dd>
              <p>
                The form input button name. Default are: 'add', or 'remove', or
                'all, or 'none', or 'toggle', or 'up', or 'down'.
              </p>
              <div class="warning c2">
                <table border="0" summary="Warning">
                  <tr>
                    <td rowspan="2" align="center" valign="top" width="48">
                      <img alt="[Warning]" src="img/admons/warning.png" />
                    </td>
                    <th align="left">
                      Warning
                    </th>
                  </tr>
                  <tr>
                    <td align="left" valign="top">
                      Default values of the name attribute are not equivalent
                      to button identifiers.
                    </td>
                  </tr>
                </table>
              </div>
            </dd>
          </dl>
        </div>
        <div class="variablelist">
          <dl>
            <dt>
              <span class="term"><em class=
              "parameter"><code>value</code></em></span>
            </dt>
            <dd>
              <p>
                The form input button text. Default are ' &gt;&gt; ', or '
                &lt;&lt; ', or ' Select All ', or ' Select None ', or ' Toggle
                Selection ', or ' Up ', or ' Down '.
              </p>
            </dd>
          </dl>
        </div>
        <div class="variablelist">
          <dl>
            <dt>
              <span class="term"><em class=
              "parameter"><code>type</code></em></span>
            </dt>
            <dd>
              <p>
                The form input button kind. Default is 'button' (Can be either
                'button' or 'image').
              </p>
            </dd>
          </dl>
        </div>
        <div class="variablelist">
          <dl>
            <dt>
              <span class="term"><em class=
              "parameter"><code>class</code></em></span>
            </dt>
            <dd>
              <p>
                A CSS class identifier in one of your stylesheets.
              </p>
            </dd>
          </dl>
        </div>
        <div class="variablelist">
          <dl>
            <dt>
              <span class="term"><em class=
              "parameter"><code>src</code></em></span>
            </dt>
            <dd>
              <p>
                URL of the image file used.
              </p>
            </dd>
          </dl>
        </div>
      </div>
